{"id":"1806.02427","submitter":"Ian Hincks","authors":"Ian Hincks, Thomas Alexander, Michal Kononenko, Benjamin Soloway,\n  David G. Cory","title":"Hamiltonian Learning with Online Bayesian Experiment Design in Practice","comments":"16 pages, 11 figures","journal-ref":null,"doi":null,"report-no":null,"categories":"quant-ph","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  Estimating parameters of quantum systems is usually done by performing a\nsequence of predetermined experiments and post-processing the resulting data.\nIt is known that online design, where the choice of the next experiment is\nbased on the most up-to-date knowledge about the system, can offer speedups to\nparameter estimation. We apply online Bayesian experiment design to a Nitrogen\nVacancy (NV) in diamond to learn the values of a five-parameter model\ndescribing its Hamiltonian and decoherence process. Comparing this to standard\npre-determined experiment sweeps, we find that we can achieve median posterior\nvariances on some parameters that are between 10 and 100 times better given the\nsame amount of data. This has applications to NV magnetometry where one of the\nHamiltonian coefficients is the parameter of interest. Furthermore, the methods\nthat we use are generic and can be adapted to any quantum device.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Wed, 6 Jun 2018 21:10:42 GMT"}],"update_date":"2018-06-08"}
